clarte: A set of flexible tools for common fMRI tasks.¶

At the center of the toolbox is the fmri_data object, which is loosely based on the fmri_data object from the Canlab toolbox (https://github.com/canlab). It is basically a wrapper for the excellent nipy suite of tools (http://nipy.org/)

At its core, this object loads, masks, resamples, and reshapes fMRI data. -basically the goal was to create a tool that handles all of the annoying/repetitive aspects of fmri analyses while being as flexible as possible.

There are two different functions for searchlight analyses: ("seachlightSphere" and "searchlightKnn"), which interact with the fmri_data object. They are highly flexible, support any analysis (via the 'pipeline' function), support parallel computation via joblib, and should be easy to use.

Non-Standard/Non-Python Dependencies:¶

  • SPM, FSL, BROCCOLI, ANTs, freesurfer
  • nibabel, nilearn, seaborn, pysurfer (pysurfer.github.io), tqdm (github.com/noamraph/tqdm)
  • Some functions use matlab (via the matlab_wrapper package)

Setup:¶

  • add clarte.py to your path
  • adjust paths in settings section
  • adjust paths in getPeaks

With this one-liner we loaded the functional volumes, calculated an implicit mask, and reshaped the data into a 2d matrix (108 volumes * 62770 voxels), a common format for many machine-learning analyses.

  • You might notice that the number of voxels in the dat.dat does not match that of the original image. This is because the dat.dat includes only voxels within the mask.

In addition to the 'background' option, which calculates the mask based on the differences with the background, there are other options too:¶

  • 'full': uses a predefined full-brain MNI mask (the path to which must be specified during setup
  • 'grey' : uses a predefined grey-brain MNI mask (the path to which must be specified during setup
  • 'epi': uses a different algorithm than the 'background' option, often fails, but worth trying if 'background' yields an unsatisfactory result
  • any path to a binary-valued image. It will be automatically resampled to the space of the functional volumes

Searchlight analyses:¶

- There are two seachlight functions¶

  • searchlightKnn: uses a k-nearest neighbors approach, in which each searchlight neighborhood consists of the k-nearest voxels, rather than a fixed sphere radius.

  • searchlightSphere: uses a sphere (obviously)

Demo:¶

  • Just for the sake of the example, let's pretend that our dat.dat represents 4 runs, with 36 volumes in each.
  • Let's create a dat.sessions vector, and then preproc the data (again):

Now, we specify the analysis we want to run (as a function).¶

  • The function must accept two inputs: X, and y:

    • X will be the functional data from the searchlight (a 2d matrix: samples*voxels)

    • y will be dat.y

  • The function must return a scalar

  • Even if the analyis is unsupervised (i.e., does not use the y vector) you must specify dat.y

    • e.g, dat.y = np.array([])

Let's do a cross-validated, leave-one-run out decoding analysis using a support vector classifier:¶

In [30]:
from sklearn.cross_validation import LeaveOneLabelOut
from sklearn.svm import LinearSVC
cv = LeaveOneLabelOut(labels=dat.sessions)
svc = LinearSVC(C=.01)

# now define the key analysis function:
def pipeline(X,y): 
    ypred = np.zeros_like(y)
    for tr,te in cv:
        ypred[te] = svc.fit(X[tr,:],y[tr]).predict(X[te,:])
    return (ypred==y).mean()

dat.pipeline = pipeline

You now are ready to call searchlightKnn

- e.g., "im = k.searchlightKnn(dat, knn=50,n_jobs=2)"

However, because it takes some time to identify the spherical neighborhoods surrounding each voxel, it can be more efficient to find the neighborhoods first, so that you can save them and re-use them.

  • This can be done with call to getSearchlights. This function outputs a data frame ('dfCoords') and numpy array ('mKnn'):

    • dfCoords:

      • (nVoxels*3) pandas dataframe representing matrix coordinates of all voxels
      • (matrix coordinates can be converted to image coordinates via nilearn.image.resampling.coord_transform)

    • mKnn:

      • (nVoxels*knn) numpy array (where knn = nVoxels per searchlight)
      • used to index dfCoords
In [32]:
# define searchlights:
knn = 50 # number of voxels per searchlight
dfCoords, mKnn = cl.getSearchlights(dat,knn)
print(dfCoords.shape)
print(mKnn.shape)
